The store is usually well stocked but there have been a few times I haven't been able to find what I need. The size of the store also means the layout can be a little confusing as well.

name: Woolworths South Melbourne
review_text:
Woolworths - the ultimate shopping destination that never sleeps! The best part about this remarkable store is its extended operating hours, remaining open until the stroke of midnight. This means that no matter how hectic your day may be, you can always rely on Woolworths to cater to your needs, even during the late hours.

One of the standout features of Woolworths is its incredibly helpful and attentive staff. Recognizing the importance of exceptional customer service, they have recently increased the number of staff members in the Deli section. This ensures that you receive prompt assistance and guidance, making your shopping experience all the more enjoyable.

Convenience is key, and Woolworths understands this perfectly. Situated in close proximity to your location, this store is easily accessible, saving you valuable time and effort. Whether you're in need of daily essentials, delectable confectionery, essential stationery, top-quality kitchen cutlery, bathroom necessities, fresh non-vegetarian items, or women's wellness products, Woolworths has got you covered. Their extensive range of products caters to all your needs, ensuring that you find everything you require under one roof.

At Woolworths, they believe in going above and beyond to meet their customers' expectations. With a wide variety of goods available, you can rest assured that you will find exactly what you're looking for. From the moment you step foot into the store until the time you leave, Woolworths strives to provide you with an exceptional shopping experience that is second to none.

So why settle for anything less? Visit Woolworths today and discover the unparalleled convenience, helpful staff, and extensive range of products that make it the ultimate shopping destination for all your needs.

Last time I had to walk all the way around to the end of the self check out to find one. I pointed it out to the worker - "the baskets are in the wrong spot...there's none by the entrance"..
And she replied, "oh really?"

15 mins later when I left and walked past the entrance again the baskets were still not replaced. Any decent worker who actually gives a stuff would have spent the 60 seconds to sort it out but it seems they prefer to inconvenience their customers.

My wife saw a mouse in there a few months ago and the staff didn't seem to care either.

The car park has a 1.5 hour free parking policy and itâ€™s ticket free, which makes for for a smooth entry and exit. My partner who is from SE Asia says that the selection of Asian groceries is also much better than the average Woolworths.

name: Woolworths South Melbourne
review_text: This store has 2 hour free parking, and number plate recognition so no tickets required. There's 2 parking levels which are quite large so you'll almost always find a space. It's also easy to drive in and out of unlike the really tight parking spots at nearby Coles. Staff are generally friendly and helpful. If you need to use a trolley, you will need a $1/$2 coin to unlock it, you can collect the coin back once you return it to the trolley bay after you've unloaded the groceries into your car. Wheelchair/pram friendly with lifts access between store & car parks. The location of this store is also quite convenient - even though the new Melbourne Square store is closer to me, I still come back to this store when I need to also drop into the post office + make a purchase from the south Melbourne market or make a purchase from Aldi or make a purchase from the pharmacy across the store etc. - it allows me to get various tasks done in one go because of its location in addition to the convenience of free parking within the locale.

name: Woolworths South Melbourne
review_text:
The vegies and fruit are always super-fresh and good quality, even late at night.

Rival Coles (in Clarendon St and Bay St) starts packing aways the vegetables and fruit from about 9pm (sometimes earlier) to put them into cold storage.  Items like lettuce and greens are stored on ice while laid out during the day, but the ice will have melted by the late evening, which is why items are put away into cold storage.  As a result of this business practice, it can be difficult to get fresh produce from Coles in the evening, and the quality of some items is not great at that hour..

By contrast, Woolworths stores much of its fresh produce in tall, moist refrigerated shelves, so that items like lettuce are still perfect in the evenings.  The items aren't stacked away in the evenings, so good quality vegies and fruit is still available, even just before midnight.

The only downside of Woolworths is that some of its items are pricier than Coles or Aldi.

Well not good enough, it took me years to convince people who witnessed me get accused, that it wasn't true, bloody humiliating. So yeah I will never do that again, but yet again I haven't since anyway but I still will always refuse to open my personal place where generally a woman's absolute personal and private property reside. Unless it is well and truelly proven prior to approached, thankyou very much  to the old middle eastern man who was somewhat polite for a secret shopper, no disrespect to you all,  we both had our views..

Might be time to give Coles a try...

Full Sized WoolWorths Store in an upscale Shopping Centre on Canning Street, North Melbourne. Offers a large selection and variety of Homeware, Groceries, Eatables, Deals etc.

The SC also has a AUSPOST Branch inside and many other Small Businesses like Coffee shop. They also have their own Bakery that bakes large selection of Breads on a daily basis.

The list of products offered is quite large and wide. Best time to Buy otherwise high-priced Items is to look forward to Discount Deals Week wherein Products are Priced at Reasonable Rates that somewhat matches Purchasing Power of the gentry.

Only if the WoolWorths could offer the Items/Goods at always Reasonable Price the people would have been so happy and their Retail Centres would be always full of happy buying customers.

name: Woolworths Melbourne Square (Southbank)
review_text:
Edit: Jan 2023
- FREE 90 min parking with min $15 spend still exist, they've now worked out how to get it to you digitally as well automatically, instantly after your shop.
-Their scan & go still generally works well. Currently still doesn't accept gift cards.
-Their fast food section is worth a visit - I always get sushi, takoyaki and spring rolls whenever I visit. Sometimes they don't have it already boxed up, but they're more than happy to make it fresh for you if the equipment is still on, so you can make a request, do your shopping, then go pick it up before heading out!

________________________________

Dec 2020
Good range of products, a lot more variety than South Melbourne store. Top floor has your dry goods and fridge/frozen food, perishables downstairs. Wheelchair accessible. Friendly staff. Free 90 min parking (one entrance via Hoff Bvd off Kavanagh st) with min $15 spend - scan the barcode on your receipt at car park. Entry/exit points with checkouts on both floors. The store also has the Scan & Go app capability which is great for keeping track of your costs as you shop, can only checkout downstairs though. The way this gets checked is : after a number of transactions (I think random) on your next check out, the system will ask for a staff to scan 5 items in your cart to make sure there are no un-scanned items, there's only one scan & go check-out though which isn't manned, so either you or someone in front of you may hold up the line, so may be worth checking if there's a line before pre-paying on the app.

Originally gave these guys 5stars for such lovely customer service (late 2021ish) but recently been less impressed. I emailed a complaint that was never dealt with or responded to.

Edit: this is the worst Woolworths I have ever been to. The way food is handled is gross, I've seen deli staff sneeze and keep working, and just now I came home to find mould on my bread. I live next door, but I'm still going to walk an extra K or 2 to do my shopping purely because of how poorly managed this Woolworths is.

Also, they close early. So if you see closing time as 'midnight' that means they shut people out at 1130pm.

Without doubt the worst Woolies in the country

review_text: Worst specials ever. This woolworths is completely overpriced and their markdowns are terrible. Sandwiches and meat that are on the brink of their use by dates are barely 50% off and still widely available for sale. Their full price sourdough loafs are $7 and on special for $6.50. Not even 10%, in this day and age they're advertising a meager saving of 50 cents. Overall all the markdowns and specials which are controlled by the store are pretty pointless. The bakery, deli and seafood section are pretty small considering it is a full sized woolies. No sight of the $20 crays that were all over the news recently.  All in all pretty unspectacular opening.

Inside the store, all shelves are well stocked, and the fresh produce is turned over regularly. I havenâ€™t spotted anything mouldy (unlike at Coles). The free parking and easy access to the freeway and Beaconsfield parade make it a magnet for rev-heads, so it is best to avoid this supermarket after 9 p.m.

When I questioned staff who at the time were filling up fridges they immediately cut me off to say that they do in fact restock V cans, but they're sold out despite the fact that the shelf in the drinks aisle is overstocked. Some super friendly staff work there and I appreciate them, but sadly this store has a lot of issues it needs to work on ASAP or their reputation in the community will continue to decline.

author_title: Everything's Shiny Captain, Not to Fret
review_text:
Pretty poor experience overall.

I was excited when this new store opened much closer to me than the South Melbourne store but there are a number of issues I've encountered.

First off, you do the Covid scan for the "centre" (Woolies, Dan's and a coffee shop) then 4 metres later you have to do a different one just for Woolies. What on earth is the point?

The plastic trolleys seem a lot smaller than the traditional ones, I certainly get a lot less in them. From the outside of the store they are also hidden from view. I went back outside to get one because I didn't see them in the store.

The store has chosen to put almost all its refrigerated produce inside cabinets. So you now have to open doors the whole time to look at prices, sell-by dates, sizes etc for all refrigerated items. It is a major pain. I hope they don't roll this out to their other stores. I hate it.

Stock has been pretty awful, both the range and the stock itself, particularly for a store I have only visited off peak when it has been virtually empty.

Some examples, on both occasions there has been just a space where the regular Lurpack should be. They also only appear to be selling the 250g size, not the much better value larger sizes. Why???

The soft drink aisles also had large gaps, the multi-pack of cans I wanted had no price against it and the sparkling water stack was completely empty. Why don't you stock the 2L Solo No Sugar and Sunkist Sugar Free?

There were many more examples of items that were simply not available on the shelves and I ended up having to do a second shop to fill the gaps.

Items like fresh orange juice were way more expensive than Coles own brand (there is no Woolies equivalent) and my regular buy of a small bottle of fresh cream has gone up from $1.59 to $1.89, maybe to help fund the refrigerated cabinets?

I had great hopes but now will be back to Aldi and Coles or the South Melbourne store.

Parking much easily than Coles Port Melbourne- they have basically gutted a warehouse and inserted the supermarket at one end and put the car park at the other - all under cover with a tall ceiling and wide driving lanes with walkways in between so you donâ€™t have to deal with other cars leaving while pushing your trolley.  Full range in store with the usual bakery, deli etc. Iâ€™d say in most areas (but not all) better than the range at Coles Port Melb.  Nice wide aisles. Letâ€™s hope they keep it nice and clean and stocked. Woolworths do have a reputation for being a bit of a grotty store. Will be a boon as the area develops with the new rezoning and apartment towers going up or planned and the high school being built opposite.
Dan Murphys attached.  Also has toilets which is a bonus for any shopper caught short.

name: Woolworths Fishermans Bend
review_text:
A very positive first impression! Store was immaculate, well stocked and the staff were eager to help. Lots of things they sell here that Coles don't. A big focus on grab and go items, vegan items, health food items, artisanal food (cheeses in particular). Lots and lots of fish and seafood options.

Quite impressed with the fact they are offering some hot food too (chicken strips etc) at the deli. All the healthier packaged options (snacks and the like) displayed near the produce area is a fantastic idea that I'm yet to see in any other supermarket.

Parking was an absolute breeze in comparison to Coles or Woolies South Melbourne. No lifts, no escalators, no parking tickets, no dark underground. Just park out front and waltz in. Very handy for grabbing things last minute. Hopefully the parking will be patrolled as workers in the area may get ideas that they can park there all day.

They also have a Sushi Sushi store and a coffee shop right near the front. Probably will be popular with commuters to the area needing a quick feed or coffee.

Love the style and feel of the store in general. Wide aisles, things seem to fit seamlessly together and very well lit. The carpark itself is quite lovely - Old factory ceiling with Colorbond steel walls. Potted trees add some greenery and colour. Feels homely and welcoming.

Overall, it's great that Coles now has some serious competition in the area and I hope Coles lift their game to this standard. Never having to drive to South Melbourne Woolies again is also great (have had several bad experiences in there). Let's hope they can keep this momentum going!

name: Woolworths Brunswick
review_text: Its hard to think of anything to say about a Woolies. What DO you say about it? Well. They are the fresh food people and I guess that's why sometimes their potted basil has caterpillars, leading to the end of my herb garden, but that's a horror story that stays between me and the Lord. What I can say however is that I love the energy their cashiers have. They're always very nice, and it's great to see a store that values diversity in hiring people! I wish they had stools or chairs so they would be afforded the basic human dignity of being able to sit down at work, but you can only expect so much from a company I guess! So, to sum it up, good food, great service, love their effort at hiring diverse people, needs more basic human rights. 4/5. Their pane di Casa is nice too.

name: Woolworths Brunswick
review_text: I've been mostly using their Click & Collect service during lockdown and it has been a very positive experience. Quick turnaround from order to pick up, $30 minimum order. I've had just one substitution (which was well chosen) and no 'out of stocks'. The drive-through is easy to access and exit, you do your own packing but you can have it all bagged ready to go. Staff are courteous, friendly and helpful. Their SMS notification/communication system is easy to follow and use. It failed on only one occasion and was sorted at the drive-through. When I've gone into the store, the staff there have been courteous, friendly and helpful. The stock range and stock levels are comparable to Coles. Store is spacious and well set out. Very happy customer.
